      "source": [
        "Every LLM vendor offers broadly 4 categories of models or model types\n",
        "1.\tText AI models – GPT 5.4, mini,nano,pro etc.,\n",
        "\n",
        "Tokens – Tokens are like a 4 letter word in English. Every sentence is broken into a token by tokenizer provided by the vendor. Ex. Anthropic, open ai provide their owne tokenizer and test tokenizer to understand the no. of tokens in a sentence.\n",
        "Now tokens are of 2 types – input tokens & output tokens\n",
        "\n",
        "Input tokens – these are the tokens from the prompts/sentence posted by the user to the model.\n",
        "Output tokens - these are the tokens consumed by the model to generate the answer for the prompt.\n",
        "\n",
        "Generally output tokens are 2-5x costlier than input tokens, as output generation takes compute resources.\n",
        "All model charge API cost per 1 million tokens consumed. Text token are cheapest while video generation tokens/pricing are costliest\n",
        "Non English language or special chars have more tokens per word as they are less commonly used in the training data of the model\n",
        "\n",
        "How each platform measure tokens:\n",
        "1.\tOpen AI – they have their own tokenizer and calculate pricing for 1M\n",
        "2.\tClaude – they have their own tokenizer by anthropic. Same as 1M\n",
        "3.\tAzure openAI – pricing is calculated same as openai as that is the baseline + additional ai services are provided on top of it\n",
        "4.\tGoogle Vertex AI – Gemini models use Google tokenizer. Claude on Vertex uses claude tokenizer. Price is per 1M tokens\n",
        "In context of CCaaS, every customer query is a input token, routing is done using input tokens and bot reply is output token\n",
        "\n",
        "OpenAI models:\n",
        "1.\tGPT 5.4 O3 – complex tasks\n",
        "2.\tMini – everyday tasks\n",
        "3.\tNano - simple tasks\n",
        "\n",
        "OpenAI has 4 types of processing modes – the way API calls to their models are made:\n",
        "1.\tStandard – pay as you go, priced by no. of API calls made. Used for contact centers etc., Real time speed meaning, each request is placed ASAP and gets the response\n",
        "Ex: Live chat, chatbot conversations\n",
        "2.\tBatch – valid within a 24hr period. Here you send a large job that has multiple API calls to be made in 1 go. The model runs this as background job when servers are less busy and shares the output in 1 go. This reduces the cost by 50%\n",
        "Ex: Non real time Reporting requirements, Generating call summaries etc.,\n",
        "3.\tFlex mode – 50% cheaper than standard. Same as batch mode, requests are sent immediately but openai runs them when server capacity is available or in background. Ex: useful for no critical tasks, where slow responses ar ok like testing etc.,\n",
        "4.\tPriority mode – 2x expensive than standard. Request/response are fast with guaranteed capacity assigned. Ex: used for SLA, mission critical tasks\n",
        "\n",
        "Types of models:\n",
        "1.\tText models: used in chatbots for any text based usecase. Comes with the 4 processing modes mentioned above. Ex GPT 5.4 costs $0.75 to $2.5 per 1M tokens for flagshipt n best value packages (mini)\n",
        "2.\tRealtime & Audio models: These are voice models. They are 8-10x costlier than the text models. GPT-realtime & gpt-realtime-mini. Costs 32/64 & 10/20. Hence enterprises need to check if they want to transcribe the voice calls (cheaper) or have a real time model respond\n",
        "\n",
        "Tools – Add ons: These are the add on we can take as per usecase\n",
        "1.\tWeb search: the chatbot is expected to do a web search before responding to. Costs $10 per 1000 searches\n",
        "2.\tFile storage searches: searching from a file storage, 0.1$ per 1GB per day. 1 GB is free\n",
        "3.\tContainer searches: python code base etc., as per sessions 0.32$ charged\n",
        "\n",
        "Fine-tuning models: Customizing the model as per enterprise data\n",
        "This involve 2 steps –\n",
        "1.\tStep 1: Fine tunings the model – since the gpt model is based on the data from internet this needs enterprise data for finetuning. So company can share their data to the model. This costs $100 per hours. Typically the process can last for 4hrs so $400 on average. This is 1 time cost\n",
        "2.\tStep 2: Inference – this is ongoing cost of using the fine tuned model. Meaning the input & response i.e., input n output tokens are 5x costlier than the standard model.\n",
        "3.\tOpenAI offers 50% discount on inference costs when data sharing is enabled. But since enterprises have PII data they wont allow this n pay in full\n",
        "4.\tBefore going ahead with fine tuning, companies can actually invest in prompt engineering – to give better prompts to the model for the right response. Post that fine tuning can be taken up\n",
        "\n",
        "Prompt Caching: system store repeated prompt context like prompt, the response, KB articles etc., n reuse them. This means instead of making an API call every time, using this 90% cost is saved on a reused cached response\n",
        "\n",
        "Monthly cost estimate:\n",
        "No. of chats in a contact center – 50K\n",
        "Avg input tokens per chat – 500\n",
        "Avg output tokens per chat – 200\n",
        "Input cost = ((500*50000)/1000000) * cost per tier/package\n",
        "Output cost = ((200*50000)/1000000) * cost per tier/package\n",
        "Total cost = input + output cost\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "\n"
